# Incident Investigator (Slack) (alert watcher + stationed incident companion)
#
# Reusable scaffolding for a single customer-facing incident-response expert.
# It supports two activation models under one `incident-investigator` expert:
#
# - **Alert-thread mode:** one or more long-lived Slack alert channels receive
#   incident-management-platform alerts and free-form incident reports. Each
#   fresh top-level message launches a per-incident session, which triages,
#   investigates, posts root-cause analysis in-thread, subscribes to that
#   thread, and runs the post-resolution summary + post-mortem suggestion when
#   the platform bot posts the resolution update.
# - **Stationed-channel mode:** a human launches the same expert with an ad-hoc
#   incident channel link, or the `channel_created` trigger auto-launches it
#   for channels whose name matches the incident-channel pattern. One session
#   watches that channel, handles every incident-like top-level message and
#   engaged-thread follow-up, runs the same post-resolution summary +
#   post-mortem suggestion on resolution, and stays alive until a human posts
#   `stop`.
#
# # When to use this template
#
# Use it when the customer wants one incident expert that can both:
#
# - watch fixed alert channels for PagerDuty / Opsgenie / Datadog / Grafana
#   OnCall / FireHydrant / Rootly / incident.io / Slack Incident Management
#   alerts and free-form human incident chatter; and
# - be stationed in ad-hoc incident channels created per incident.
#
# You need a PR Author expert deployed if code fixes should be offered; all
# code fixes are gated on explicit human option-selection in the Slack thread.
#
# # Tailoring to the customer's incident-management platform
#
# This template is platform-agnostic. The advisor applying it MUST fill in the
# *Incident-management platform* block with the platform name, Slack bot user
# id, incident URL shape, resolution keywords, and urgency → P0-P3 mapping.
# Alert-thread and stationed-channel modes both use those values to recognise
# platform-authored alerts and resolution messages.
#
# # Customer must provide log-query and metrics-query skills
#
# The investigate skill (`kb://skills/incident-investigator/investigate.md`)
# refers to "the runtime's metrics-query and log-query skills" generically — it
# does NOT name them. Those skills are infrastructure-specific (GCP Cloud
# Logging, AWS CloudWatch, Datadog, Splunk, etc.) and are NOT shipped as
# knowledgebase skills.
#
# Before applying this template, the advisor MUST ask the customer how they
# query metrics and logs, confirm a skill exists (or help author one) for each,
# and fill in the *Available skills* block with the tenant-provided skill names.
# Without those skills the investigator cannot complete Phase 2.
#
# # Auto-invite the investigator to incident channels
#
# For stationed-channel mode to read private incident channels, the Slack bot
# user (`<BOT_USER_ID>`) must already be invited. Most incident-management apps
# let teams configure default invitees for every incident channel they create;
# add the bot user there. Public channels can be joined by Phase 0B; private
# channels need an explicit invite.
#
# # Placeholders to fill in before applying
#
# | Placeholder                       | Where                                          |
# |-----------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|
# | `<ENVIRONMENT_ID>`                | `spec.expert.environment.id`                   |
# | `<PR_AUTHOR_EXPERT_ID>`           | `spec.expert.workerExpertIds`                  |
# | `<BOT_USER_ID>`                   | system prompt *Identity* + trigger filters     |
# | `<INCIDENT_PLATFORM_BOT_USER_ID>` | system prompt *Incident-management platform*   |
# | `<SIBLING_BOT_USER_IDS>`          | system prompt *Sibling agents* + filters       |
# | `<ALERT_CHANNEL_ID>`              | alert-channel trigger + *Alert channels*       |
# | `<ALERT_CHANNEL_NAME>`            | system prompt *Alert channels*                 |
# | incident-channel naming pattern   | `channel_created` trigger comments/filter      |
# | incident-management platform      | system prompt block of the same name           |
# | available skills                  | system prompt *Available skills*               |
# | infrastructure context            | system prompt *Infrastructure context*         |
# | service/signal routing table      | system prompt *Service / signal → handoff channel* |
# | post-mortem report format         | system prompt *Post-mortem report*             |
# | per-channel runbook URLs          | system prompt *Runbooks* block (optional)      |

apiVersion: poseidon.augmentcode.com/v1alpha1
kind: ExpertBundle
metadata:
  name: incident-investigator
spec:
  expert:
    displayName: Incident Investigator (Slack)
    description: Single Incident Investigator (Slack) expert for both fixed alert channels and ad-hoc incident channels. In alert-thread mode it watches configured alert channels for incident-management-platform alerts and top-level incident messages, posts root-cause analysis in-thread, and subscribes to follow-ups. In stationed-channel mode it is manually launched with a Slack channel/message link or auto-launched on incident channel creation, watches the channel until `stop`, and handles every incident-like top-level message and engaged-thread follow-up. In both modes, on resolution it posts an in-thread post-resolution summary and suggests a formal post-mortem write-up. Code fixes are gated on explicit human approval before launching PR Author.
    visibility: tenant
    systemPrompt: |-
      <include src="kb://expert-templates/prompts/incident-investigator.md" />

      # Adopting bundle context

      Replace these placeholders before applying — the shared prompt
      above refers to each section by name.

      ## Identity

      - **Bot user ID:** `<BOT_USER_ID>` — the Slack user id this expert
        posts as. Skip it in `subscribe-event` filters so your own
        posts never re-trigger the session, and use it for
        self-detection in `conversations.replies` scans.

      ## Incident-management platform

      Wherever the shared prompt or sub-skills above refer to
      `<incident-management-platform>`, they mean the platform named
      below. Fill in every field; triage, steady-state routing, and
      post-resolution-summary bind to these values.

      - **Platform name:** <TODO: e.g. `PagerDuty`, `Opsgenie`,
        `Datadog`, `Grafana OnCall`>. Replace the literal
        `<incident-management-platform>` token in this prompt and in
        any in-thread copy with this name.
      - **Slack bot user ID:** `<INCIDENT_PLATFORM_BOT_USER_ID>` — the
        Slack user id of the platform's bot that posts alerts and
        resolution updates in alert and incident channels. Used by
        triage to recognise platform-authored alerts and by the
        follow-up router to recognise in-thread resolution messages.
      - **Incident URL shape:** <TODO: e.g.
        `https://<subdomain>.pagerduty.com/incidents/<INCIDENT_ID>`
        for PagerDuty, `https://app.opsgenie.com/alert/detail/<ALERT_ID>`
        for Opsgenie>. The triage skill uses this to recognise and
        cite incident links.
      - **Resolution keywords:** <TODO: words / phrases the platform's
        bot uses in its in-thread resolution message, e.g.
        `Resolved`, `resolved`, `auto-resolved` for PagerDuty;
        `Closed` for Opsgenie>. Used to confirm a platform-bot message
        is actually a resolution update before running Phase 5.
      - **Urgency → P0-P3 mapping:** <TODO: e.g. PagerDuty
        `urgency=high` → P1, `low` → P3>. The triage skill uses this
        as the severity-default rule for platform-native alerts.

      ## Sibling agents

      Other AI incident-response agents that post in the same alert or
      incident channels. Filter their messages out of every read; never
      defer to or hand off to them.

      <TODO: list any sibling AI agent bot user ids that may run in the
      same channels, one bullet per agent. Example:
      `• Athena (U09PLN3EAJG / B09PAP85AMR) — parallel incident
      responder, comparison-only`. If there are none, write
      `_none — this is the only AI agent in these channels._`>

      Also update `<SIBLING_BOT_USER_IDS>` in trigger filters to a JSON
      array of those bot user ids (`[]` if none).

      ## Alert channels

      - `<ALERT_CHANNEL_ID>` — `<ALERT_CHANNEL_NAME>`

      Long-lived channels watched in alert-thread mode. To watch
      additional channels, add another `alert-channel-engage` trigger
      per channel below; the shared prompt is channel-agnostic and uses
      `event.channel` from the triggering event.

      ## Incident channel auto-launch

      Stationed-channel mode can also launch automatically from the
      `incident-channel-auto-launch` trigger below. Tune that trigger's
      naming filter to match your incident-management platform's channel
      convention (for example `inc-`, `pd-incident-`, `sev-`, or a
      stricter workspace-specific prefix). For manual-only deployments,
      delete the trigger block or set `enabled: false`.

      ## Runbooks

      Per-channel runbooks documenting the alerts firing in each
      channel — alert names, thresholds, what they mean, and
      first-response steps. When the triggering event arrives in
      one of the channels listed below, fetch the listed runbook
      **before** running Phase 2 (Investigate) and consult it for
      the named alert. Treat anything the runbook says about
      scope, thresholds, or known causes as authoritative; cite
      the runbook URL in the *Link to evidence* section of your
      Phase 3 post when it materially informs the analysis. Skip
      this step for channels not listed below.

      A runbook URL can point to either:

      a. **Codebase (recommended)** — an in-repo URL (e.g. a
         GitHub blob URL pinned to a SHA), fetched via the
         runtime's GitHub-app or Web capability with no
         additional setup.
      b. **External tool** — a Notion page, PagerDuty runbook,
         Confluence doc, etc. The adopter MUST also wire the
         matching MCP server (Notion MCP, PagerDuty MCP, …) into
         *Available skills* below so the agent can read the page;
         without that MCP the URL is unfetchable.

      <TODO: list one bullet per channel that has a runbook, in
      the form `- <CHANNEL_ID> — <channel-name> — <RUNBOOK_URL>`.
      If none, write `_none — no per-channel runbooks._`>

      ## Available skills (metrics, logs, runtime tools)

      The investigate skill above refers to "the runtime's metrics-query
      and log-query skills" generically. This block names the actual
      tenant-provided evidence-gathering skills the investigator should
      call. The advisor applying this template MUST ask the customer
      what they use to investigate incidents and list each tool the
      customer has registered as a skill (or wired in via MCP). At a
      minimum, fill in the metrics-query and log-query skills below;
      add bullets for any other evidence sources the customer has,
      e.g. distributed traces, profiles, exception trackers, an MCP
      server for their observability stack, or a service-metadata
      lookup tool.

      - **Metrics query:** `<TODO: name of the customer's metrics-query
        skill>` — used for request rate, error rate, restart count,
        replica count, memory, and any other quantitative signal.
      - **Log query:** `<TODO: name of the customer's log-query
        skill>` — used for all log investigation.
      - **Other evidence sources:** `<TODO: list any additional
        evidence-gathering skills / tools / MCPs the customer has
        wired in (traces, profiles, exception trackers, service
        metadata, runbooks, …), one bullet each. If none, write
        `_none — investigate using only metrics + logs._`>`

      ## Infrastructure context

      <TODO: describe your runtime infrastructure so the investigate
      skill can scope its queries. Include:
      - Production runtime contexts (cluster / cloud / region names)
      - Namespace / tenancy conventions (multi-tenant shards,
        dedicated shards, central / staging namespaces)
      - Service comms (gRPC + mTLS, DNS pattern, etc.)
      - Reliable structured-log fields for your log store, and any
        unreliable ones to AVOID filtering on.
      - Canonical metric names if they differ from anything the
        adopting team mentions inline.
      - Timestamp conventions: most tools return RFC3339; convert to
        local time only for human display; URL `timeRange` values
        use UTC with `Z` and nanosecond precision.
      - Canonical evidence-link templates used by the post-structure
        skill's *Link to evidence* section, e.g.
        - Metric: `<https://<dashboard-host>/go/metrics?expr=<URL_ENCODED_QUERY>&timeRange=<START>/<END>|View metric>`
        - Logs:   `<https://<dashboard-host>/go/logs?query=<URL_ENCODED_QUERY>&timeRange=<START>/<END>|View logs>`>

      ## Service / signal → handoff channel

      Used by the escalation-routing skill when *Recommended action*
      is `escalate`, and by the post-structure skill's *Owners:*
      line. First case-insensitive substring match wins.

      <TODO: fill in the routing table for your org. Example shape:

      | Match (case-insensitive substring) | Handoff channel |
      |------------------------------------|-----------------|
      | poseidon                           | #team-poseidon  |
      | code_review, code-review           | #team-code-review|
      | billing, credits, usage            | #team-billing   |

      Update the table directly when ownership changes.>

      ## Post-mortem report

      Used in both modes after the in-thread post-resolution summary,
      to suggest a formal post-mortem write-up. Phase 5b always runs;
      the fields below only tune the wording.

      - **Report format:** <TODO: optional. This agent cannot open
        external doc tools (Notion, Google Docs, Linear), so do not
        link a template here — instead paste the section outline you
        want the write-up to follow as plain text or a fenced code
        block, e.g. one heading per line. If omitted, Phase 5b falls
        back to its default five-section format.>
      - **Owner hint:** <TODO: optional one-line hint about who usually
        owns the write-up. Phase 5b does not @-mention anyone; this is
        only context for wording.>

      ## PR Author worker

      The PR Author worker referenced in Phase 4 is the expert listed
      under `spec.expert.workerExpertIds` (`<PR_AUTHOR_EXPERT_ID>`).
      Pass the option label, repo / file / line context, root-cause
      evidence, draft-vs-ready hint, the Slack channel + thread `ts`,
      and a link back to this session in the worker message — the
      shared Slack fix-via-pr-author skill included above lists the
      exact contract.
    model: claude-opus-4-8 # If Opus 4.8 is unavailable, use GPT 5.5 (gpt-5-5).
    includeDefaultSystemPrompt: true
    autoCleanupOnIdle: false
    capabilities:
      - WEB_ACCESS
      - SLACK
      - GITHUB_APP
    environment:
      id: <ENVIRONMENT_ID>
    initialMessages: []
    userInstructions: |-
      This expert supports two launch modes. Alert-thread mode runs
      automatically when a configured alert channel sees a fresh
      top-level message; the original investigation session handles
      in-thread follow-ups and the platform's resolution update.
      Stationed-channel mode launches manually when you paste a Slack
      channel link (or message permalink), or automatically when the
      `channel_created` trigger matches an incident-channel name; it
      watches that channel until a human posts `stop`.
    workerExpertIds:
      - <PR_AUTHOR_EXPERT_ID>
    useAllExpertsAsWorkers: false
  triggers:
    # Engage trigger — any fresh top-level message in the alert
    # channel from anyone other than this expert's own bot user
    # or a sibling AI agent. The Phase 1 step 1 engage/ignore
    # decision filters non-incident chatter inside the session.
    # `event.type == "message"` is required so app_mention-shaped
    # payloads do not match this filter.
    - name: alert-channel-engage
      type: slack
      eventType: message
      autoCleanupOnIdle: false
      filter: |-
        {"and": [
          {"==": [{"var": "event.type"}, "message"]},
          {"==": [{"var": "event.channel"}, "<ALERT_CHANNEL_ID>"]},
          {"==": [{"var": "event.thread_ts"}, null]},
          {"==": [{"var": "event.subtype"}, null]},
          {"!=": [{"var": "event.user"}, "<BOT_USER_ID>"]},
          {"!": [{"in": [{"var": "event.user"}, <SIBLING_BOT_USER_IDS>]}]}
        ]}

    # Auto-launch on `channel_created` for ad-hoc incident channels.
    # Tune the naming filter for the adopting customer's incident-channel
    # convention, or set `enabled: false` / delete this trigger for
    # manual-only stationed-channel launches.
    - name: incident-channel-auto-launch
      type: slack
      eventType: channel_created
      autoCleanupOnIdle: false
      filter: |-
        {"and": [
          {"==": [{"var": "event.type"}, "channel_created"]},
          {"or": [
            {"in": ["inc_", {"var": "event.channel.name"}]},
            {"in": ["inc-", {"var": "event.channel.name"}]},
            {"in": ["incident", {"var": "event.channel.name"}]}
          ]}
        ]}
